com.googlecode.kevinarpe.papaya.string.joiner
Interface MapJoiner2

All Superinterfaces:
MapJoiner2Settings<MapJoiner2>, SharedJoiner2Settings<MapJoiner2,MapJoiner2>
public interface MapJoiner2
extends MapJoiner2Settings<MapJoiner2>

Extension of Google Guava's Joiner.MapJoiner. To construct a new instance, see Joiner2Utils.withSeparator(String) and Joiner2Utils.withSeparator(char).

Differences to Joiner.MapJoiner:

  • MapJoiner2Settings.withKeyQuotes(String, String): Prefix and suffix for each joined key
  • MapJoiner2Settings.withValueQuotes(String, String): Prefix and suffix for each joined value
  • Default text for null keys and values is "null". This matches the behavior of Formatter. By default, class Joiner will throw a NullPointerException when joining a null key or value, unless Joiner.useForNull(String) is called before joining. This is a source of many surprising/annoying/accidental runtime exceptions.
  • SharedJoiner2Settings.useForNoElements(String): During a join, if no map entries are found, this text is used. When joining map entries for an exception or log message, "(empty)" is a good value to indicate to (exception and log) readers that no map entries were found.
  • Uses interface MapJoiner2, instead of a concrete class. This follows JavaEE design principles, and is helpful for mocking and testing. Due to Java interface limitations with generic methods, the methods appendTo(Appendable, *) are slightly different from Joiner.MapJoiner. The Appendable reference is not a generic type (for input and output).
  • All settings may always be changed, e.g., key-value separator, null key text, etc. Class Joiner.MapJoiner does now allow these attributes to be set more than once.
  • Settings accessors, e.g., SharedJoiner2Settings.withKeyValueSeparator(String).
  • Default settings are available as public static final members, e.g., Joiner2Utils.DEFAULT_KEY_NULL_TEXT.

See SharedJoiner2Settings for an inheritance diagram.

Examples: 

Joiner2Utils.withSeparator(", ").withQuotes("[", "]").withKeyValueSeparator("=")
     .join(map) -> "[a=1], [b=2], [c=3], ..."
 Joiner2Utils.withSeparator(", ").withQuotes("[", "]").withKeyValueSeparator("=")
     .join(mapWithNulls) -> "[a=1], [b=2], [null=3], [c=4], ..."
 Joiner2Utils.withSeparator(", ").withQuotes("[", "]").withKeyValueSeparator("=").skipNulls(true)
     .join(mapWithNulls) -> "[a=1], [b=2], [c=3], ..."
 Joiner2Utils.withSeparator(", ").withQuotes("[", "]").withKeyValueSeparator("=").useForNoElements("(empty)")
     .join(emptyMap) -> "(empty)"

appendTo

Appendable appendTo(Appendable appendable,
                    Iterator<? extends Map.Entry<?,?>> partIter)
                    throws IOException
Appends all remaining map entries from an Iterator to an instance of Appendable.

Due to Java interface limitations with generic methods, this method signature is slightly different to Joiner.appendTo(Appendable, Iterator). The Appendable reference is not a generic type (for input and output).

Parameters:
appendable - where to append text. Must not be null.
partIter - stream of map entries to join. Must not be null. Must not contain null map entries
Returns:
argument appendable (for method chaining)
Throws:
NullPointerException - if appendable or partIter (or its elements) are null
IOException - if appendable throws an IOException
See Also:
appendTo(Appendable, Iterable), appendTo(Appendable, Map), appendTo(StringBuilder, Iterator), join(Iterator)
